08879nam a22009375i 9789814345262DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20112011si     fo  d z      eng d  a2011315681  a97898143452627 a10.1355/97898143452622doi  a(DE-B1597)492061  a(OCoLC)1041979745  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG00aDS523.4.P67bP67 2011 7aHIS0480002bisacsh0481pa950qDE-10100aPortuguese and Luso-Asian Legacies in Southeast Asia, 1511-2011, vol. 1 :bThe Making of the Luso-Asian World: Intricacies of Engagement /ced. by Laura Jarnagin. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tLIST OF CHARTS, FIGURES AND TABLES -- tA TRIBUTE TO GLENN JOSEPH AMES -- tPREFACE -- tLIST OF Contributors -- tGLOSSARY -- tIntroduction: Towards Clarity through Complexity -- tPart One. Adaptations and Transitions in the South and Southeast Asian Theatres, Sixteenth through Eighteenth Centuries -- t1. Supplying Simples for the Royal Hospital: An Indo-Portuguese Medicinal Garden in Goa (1520–1830) -- t2. Malacca in the Era of Viceroy Linhares (1629–35) -- t3. From Meliapor to Mylapore, 1662–1749: The Portuguese Presence in São Tomé between the Quṭb Shāhī Conquest and Its Incorporation into British Madras -- t4. Eighteenth-Century Diplomatic Relations between Portuguese Macao and Ayutthaya: The 1721 Debt Repayment Embassy from Macao -- t5. Continuities in Bengal’s Contact with the Portuguese and Its Legacy: A Community’s Future Engangled with the Past -- tPart Two. Dispersion, Mobility and Demography from the Sixteenth into the Twenty-first Centuries -- t6. The Luso-Asians and Other Eurasians: Their Domestic and Diasporic Identities -- t7. The Population of the Portuguese Estado da Índia, 1750–1820: Sources and Demographic Trends -- t8. Flying with the Papagaio Verde (Green Parrot): An Indo-Portuguese Folkloric Motif in South and Southeast Asia -- tPart Three. Mixed Legacies: The Portuguese and Luso-Asians in the Twentieth and Twenty-first Centuries -- t9. Portuguese Communities in East and Southeast Asia during the Japanese Occupation -- t10. Indo-Portuguese Literature and the Goa of Its Writers -- t11. Binding Ties of Miscegenation and Identity: The Narratives of Henrique Senna Fernandes (Macao) and Rex Shelley (Singapore) -- t12. Portuguese Past, Still Imperfect: Revisiting Asia in Luso-Diasporic Writing -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"In 1511, a Portuguese expedition under the command of Afonso de Albuquerque arrived on the shores of Malacca, taking control of the prosperous Malayan port-city after a swift military campaign. Portugal, a peripheral but then technologically advanced country in southwestern Europe since the latter fifteenth century, had been in the process of establishing solid outposts all along Asia's litoral in order to participate in the most active and profitable maritime trading routes of the day. As it turned out, the Portuguese presence and influence in the Malayan Peninsula and elsewhere in continental and insular Asia expanded far beyond the sphere of commerce and extended over time well into the twenty-first century. Five hundred years later, a conference held in Singapore brought together a large group of scholars from widely different national, academic and disciplinary contexts, to analyse and discuss the intricate consequences of Portuguese interactions in Asia over the longue durée. The result of these discussions is a stimulating set of case studies that, as a rule, combine original archival and/or field research with innovative historiographical perspectives. Luso-Asian communities, real and imagined, and Luso-Asian heritage, material and symbolic, are studied with depth and insight. The range of thematic, chronological and geographic areas covered in these proceeding is truly remarkable, showing not only the extraordinary relevance of revisiting Luso-Asian interactions in the longer term, but also the surprising dynamism within an area of studies which seemed on the verge of exhaustion. After all, archives from all over the world, from Rio de Janeiro to London, from Lisbon to Rome, and from Goa to Macao, might still hold some secrets on the subject of Luso-Asian relations, when duly explored by resourceful scholars." - Rui M. Loureiro, Centro de Historia de Alem-Mar, Lisbon "This two-volume set pulls together several interdisciplinary studies historicizing Portuguese 'legacies' across Asia over a period of approximately five centuries (ca. 1511-2011). It is especially recommended to readers interested in the broader aspects of the early European presence in Asia, and specifically on questions of politics, colonial administration, commerce, societal interaction, integration, identity, hybridity, religion and language." - Associate Professor Peter Borschberg, Department of History, National University of Singapore  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPortuguesezSoutheast AsiaxEthnic identityvCongresses. 0aPortuguesezSoutheast AsiaxHistoryvCongresses. 0aPortuguese--Southeast Asia--Ethnic identity--Congresses. 0aPortuguese--Southeast Asia--History--Congresses. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh1 aAranha, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhattacharya, Ujjayan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByrne, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDisney, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, K. David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJa